To complete the proof, we need to express the norms in terms of expectations and apply the Holder inequality for expectations. For a finite space, the $L^p$ norm is the $p$-th root of the expectation of the $p$-th power of the function's absolute value. For a Holder triple $p, q, r$, we have $1/p + 1/q = 1/r$ (up to reciprocal relations), and the Holder inequality for expectations gives us $\mathbb{E}[X \cdot Y] \leq \mathbb{E}[X]^p \cdot \mathbb{E}[Y]^q$.

